reviewText: CONTENTS of POWER OF EVIL 4 Movie Pack:DIE HARD DRACULA-- A modern twist on the Dracula story. An American wandering through Europe happens upon Dracula's castle, where he sees a woman that looks exactly like his recently deceased girlfriend. Three different actors portray Count D.GIRLS NIGHT OUT-- Terror trio introduced by "The Professor" include "Girls Night Out," "The Creep" and "Blood Moon Rising."THE HARVESTERS-- Although this one isn't as described on the box, it's actually more popular with poll respondents at imdb.com than the "gang of misfits and their lesbian leader" horror film you were expecting. This "Harvesters" is a thriller about a heart transplant recipient who later goes in search of the donor's parents. She discovers the dead boy's mom knows nothing about the donation and her further investigations lead to big trouble.UNHINGED-- Temporarily banned in Britain gorefest. Three college girls crash their car in a remote area during a rainstorm and spend the night with an oddball family at a creepy old mansion. Has a surprise ending.For more bizarre indie horror films check out  theWICKED INTENTIONS 4 Movie Pack, also from BRENTWOOD.BRENTWOOD's 4-fers are nicely priced movie bundles. Video and sound quality of these digitally unrestored public domain films is generally fine. Discs are dual-side recorded..Parenthetical numbers preceding titles are 1 to 10 viewer poll ratings found at a film resource website.(3.6) Creepy Tales: Girls Night Out (2003) - Scott Schiaffo/Samantha Turk/Gene Moore/Frank Weldon/Joe Hefferman (as The Professor)(1.6) Die Hard Dracula (1998) - Bruce Glover/Denny Sachem/Kerry Dustin/Ernest M. Garcia/Chaba Hrotko/Tom McGowan(4.6) The Harvesters (2000) - Crystal Amber/Richard Gross/Rueben Grundy/Robert Lee/Diane Luby Lane(5.0) Unhinged (1982) - Laura Munson/Janet Penner/Sara Ansley/Virginia Settle/John Morrison

reviewText: I was about to buy the DVD for UNHINGED (Banned in Britain! OOH!) when I saw that it was on here for the same price with three others.  Now that's a bargain.  UNHINGED was great, and I'm loving CREEPY TALES: GIRLS NIGHT OUT.  DIE HARD DRACULA I still haven't finished, but it looks like cheesy fun.But the 4th film?  THE HARVESTERS? From the description on the back, I was really excited about that one...but as a previous reviewer stated, the movie on the disc doesn't match up to what is described on the box.  The movie on here isn't bad per se, but isn't really a horror movie and doesn't fit in with the other flicks on here.  I wish I knew who to complain to about that...But other than that problem, the other movies on here are well worth the cost.  You would spend as much, if not more, renting them each individually.

reviewText: If you're a fan of no budget horror you can do a lot worse than this entertaining little flick! The movie is an anthology of 3 separate horror tales, all of which are worth watching, and one in particular that is very clever and highly original. Each tale is presented by a vampire 'horror host' in the vein of the old UHF 'creature feature' shows.The first segment is about an axe murderer who escapes a local asylum and menaces 2 cute women in the woods at night (yeah, I know - not too original but it's fun). The FX are awful in this segment but there is one excellent bloody head shot that is pretty cool. The storyline segues from the axe murderer plot to a strange and kinky elderly couple in the woods who think that the blonde is their long lost daughter. This scene gets pretty weird as they begin to discipline her in bizarre ways. Lots of chasing around in the woods and 'boob bouncing fu' from the blonde damsel who somehow runs into 2 different pervs in separate scenes who each bind & gag her(!) This is the strangest (but fastest paced and most entertaining) segment of the 3 in this anthology.Next the second segment involves a woman who becomes paranoid that a fellow employee may be planning to kill her (or is she?). There's no way to give this a more detailed description without ruining the plot. This is the most original segment of the 3 and delivers a stunning twist!The third installment is a straightforward brutal werewolf segment about people trapped in a house who are besieged by the aforementioned lycanthropy. Awful 'FX' abound (including the generic werewolf mask) but it's fun in a charming campy sort of way.The stories are all presented in a SLIGHTLY tongue-in-cheek way but they never fully wink at the audience. The scripts are sometimes well written, sometimes jaw-droppingly awful, but if you're a forgiving no-budget movie lover like me you won't hold it against this fun little cheesy horror flick.
